  From: Cathal Garvey <cathalgarvey@cathalgarvey.me>
>Without getting into the issue of whether patents encourage innovation..=
=C2=A0
>I do think that medical devices are a special case. If you have a heart=20
>implant, that thing needs to be "unhackable", but also totally=20
>verifiably safe. So there should be firmware signing, no mutable state,=20
>verifiable memory safety...but the code should be open source, and if=20
>need be the firmware signing key for each device (needs to be different=20
>for each device!) should be accessible by a legitimate owner.

>So, no more remote-hackable heart implants, but doctors and cardiac=20
>technicians can still apply critical patches and inspect the source for=20
>sanity.

It should be fairly simple to protect against heart-implant hacks. =C2=A0Fi=
rst, communication with them is probably limited to inductively-coupled sig=
nalling, at a fairly high level. =C2=A0Secondly, it should be based on a tw=
o-way challenge/response system: =C2=A0The external device signals a code, =
call it a password, to which the implant would respond with a reply, which =
itself includes a randomized code. =C2=A0The external device reads that ran=
domized code, processes it in some way (presumably a hash), and retransmits=
 it to the implant. =C2=A0Only if the implanted device receives what it con=
siders the correct code, would it allow further manipulation. =C2=A0Presuma=
bly, any attempt to illegitimately access such a device wouldn't be close e=
nough to read the implant's reply signals, and thus couldn't proceed furthe=
r.
"Do you have have a match?". =C2=A0 "No, but I have a lighter". =C2=A0"Even=
 better". =C2=A0 "Until they go wrong".

=C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0 =C2=A0Jim Bell
  
